Getting an eye-pee address: static versus d-h-c-p.

An interface needs an address before it can communicate at all, and there are two ways to give it one. The first is d-h-c-p, the dynamic host configuration protocol. With d-h-c-p the interface effectively broadcasts a question to the network, asking whether anyone has a configuration for it, and a d-h-c-p server, usually your router or a corporate server, replies with an address, a subnet mask, a gateway, and a list of dee-en-ess servers. The client periodically renews this lease. Most laptops, desktops, virtual machines, and cloud instances get their address this way.

The second is a static address, which you configure by hand. The machine never asks anyone; it simply holds that address permanently. This is used for servers that need a predictable, unchanging address, things like a dee-en-ess server, a router, or a web server, as well as printers and network equipment.

You decide between static and d-h-c-p on a per-interface basis in your network configuration, and which tool you use depends on the distribution. On most modern systems, including ubuntu desktop and the red hat family, that tool is network-manager, driven from the command line by n-m-c-l-i. On ubuntu server you will often meet net-plan, which reads a y-a-m-l file and applies it through one of the underlying services. Minimal and cloud images may use systemd-networkd directly with its own configuration files. For the exam, expect network-manager with n-m-c-l-i, or net-plan on ubuntu server, since most distributions today are built on network-manager.
